               <msContents>
                  <summary><persName role="att trl" key="person_89770781"
                     ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/89770781">Avicenna (980–1037)</persName> allegedly
                     translated  this work entitled <title xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc" type="alt" key="work_3251"
                        >Sū‘ālhā-yi Nūshirvān va Javābhā-yi Buzurjmihr</title> (Questions of
                     Nūshirvān and Answers of Buzurjmihr) better known as <title key="work_3251"
                        >Ẓafarnāmah-’i Buzurgmihr </title> (Book of Conquest of Buzurgmihr). It
                     presents a series of moral and philosophical queries posed by <persName
                        xml:lang="en" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/308254530" key="person_308254530"
                        role="subject" change="#role-assignment #ids-cleanup">Khusrov I Anushirvan
                        (501-579)</persName> followed by replies of his vizir <persName
                        xml:lang="en" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/14650184" key="person_14650184"
                        role="subject" change="#role-assignment">Buzurgmihr Bakhtagān</persName>.
                     While unsigned, Dehli Head Treasurer <persName key="person_f3560" role="scr"
                        change="#role-assignment">Rā'i Rājā Lāl Jī (1838–1885)</persName>, probably
                     completed this volume, given its hand and similar layout to <ref
                        target="https://www.fihrist.org.uk/catalog/manuscript_7151"><idno>Persian MS
                           649</idno></ref>, another copy of the same work that he signed. He
                     probably finished it for <persName cert="high" type="supplied"
                        key="person_f830" role="pat" change="#role-assignment">Colonel George
                        William Hamilton (1807-1868)</persName> during the latter's tenure as
                     Commissioner of Delhi between <date calendar="#Gregorian" from="1862" to="1867"
                        >1862 to 1867</date>. </summary>
                  <msItem xml:id="Persian_MS_650-item1">
                     <author key="person_89770781" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf">
                        <persName xml:lang="en">Avicenna, 980–1037</persName>; <lb/>
                        <persName xml:lang="ar-Latn-x-lc">Ibn Sīnā</persName>; <lb/>
                        <persName xml:lang="ar">ابن سينا</persName>; <lb/>
                     </author>
                     <editor cert="high" key="person_f3560" role="scr">
                        <persName xml:lang="ur-Latn-x-lc" role="scr">Rā'i Rājā Lāl Jī,
                           1838–1885</persName>
                     </editor>
                     <title xml:lang="ar-Latn-x-lc" type="main" key="work_3251">Ẓafarnāmah-‘i
                        Buzurgmihr</title>
                     <title xml:lang="fa" type="main" key="work_3251">ظفرنامهٔ بزرگمهر</title>
                     <title xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc" type="alt" key="work_3251">Sū‘ālhā-yi Nūshirvān
                        va Javābhā-yi Buzurjmihr</title>
                     <title xml:lang="fa" type="alt" key="work_3251">سؤالهای نوشیروان و جوابهای
                        بزرجمهر</title>
                     <title xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc" type="alt" key="work_3251">Sū‘ālhā-yi Nūshirvān
                        va Javābhā-yi Buzurgmihr</title>
                     <title xml:lang="fa" type="alt" key="work_3251">سؤالهای نوشیروان و جوابهای
                        بزرگمهر</title>
                     <rubric xml:lang="fa"><locus from="1b" to="1b"> برگ ۱پ (folio 1b):</locus>
                        سؤالهای نوشیروان پادشاه و جوابهای بزرجمهر وزیر. نشان دوست صادق چیشت؟ جواب: </rubric>
                     <incipit xml:lang="fa" type="basmalla"><locus from="1b" to="1b"> برگ ۱پ (folio
                           1b):</locus> سوال: از خداوند تعالی چه باید خواست؟ جواب: خیر و عافیت دارین </incipit>
                     <explicit xml:lang="ar"><locus from="6a " to="6a">برگ ۶ر (folio 6a):</locus>
                        سوال: نشان دوست صادق چیشت؟ جواب: آنکه در تنگی ناری نو کند و از بدی ترا مانع
                        آید و باز دارد. </explicit>
                     <colophon>No colophon.</colophon>
                     <textLang mainLang="fa">Persian</textLang>
                     <note>A prior record misattributed authorship of this work to the scribe.
                        Eldest son of British agent and informant Munshī Jiwān Lāl (1806–1884), who
                        served as secretary to the last Mughal emperor, Bahadur Shah II (1775–1862,
                        r. 1837–1857), Rājā Lāl worked as Head Treasurer of Delhi in the early
                        British Raj administration. He also copied calligraphy specimens for
                        Hamilton, including <ref
                           target="https://www.fihrist.org.uk/catalog/manuscript_26598"
                           ><idno>Persian MS 998J</idno></ref>. For other copies of this work
                        held in the Rylands, see <ref
                           target="https://www.fihrist.org.uk/catalog/manuscript_7154"><idno>Persian
                              MS 651</idno></ref> and <ref
                                 target="https://www.fihrist.org.uk/catalog/manuscript_7292"
                                 >786/5</ref>.</note>

                  </msItem>
               </msContents>
               <physDesc>
                  <objectDesc form="codex">
                     <supportDesc material="chart">
                        <support>Textblock of cross-grained, thin-weight European-manufactured
                           externally sized and polished violet wove bearing a stationery or
                           papermill blind embossed marks, and pink mould-made laid letter papers,
                           the latter measuring 7 laid lines per cm and 27 mm between laid lines.
                           All inset within bifolia margins of thin-weight, flocked, externally
                           sized and polished, ivory-coloured handmade <material>paper</material>
                           probably handmade in the <placeName cert="high"
                              ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7000208" key="place_7000208"
                              >Indian subcontinent</placeName> with ~16 laid lines per cm and no
                           discernible chain lines.</support>
                        <extent>
                           <measure unit="folio" quantity="7">7 folios, 2 flyleaves (ff. i + 7 +
                              i)</measure>. <dimensions type="leaf" unit="mm">
                              <height>263</height>
                              <width>164</width>
                           </dimensions>
                           <dimensions type="written" unit="mm">
                              <height>203</height>
                              <width>115</width>
                           </dimensions>
                        </extent>
                        <foliation xml:id="modern">Pencilled Arabic numerals added to the upper-left
                           corners of the a sides, which commence on folio <locus from="1Aa"
                              to="1Aa">1Aa</locus>, hence under by one.</foliation>

                        <collation> 1III+1(6). <catchwords>No catchwords.</catchwords></collation>


                        <condition>In fair condition, with minimal insect damage to the lower
                           margins throughout.</condition>
                     </supportDesc>


                     <layoutDesc>
                        <layout columns="1" ruledLines="7" n="mistara"> Written in 1 column with 7
                           lines per page. Ruled with a <hi rend="italic">misṭarah</hi> hand
                           guide.</layout>
                     </layoutDesc>
                  </objectDesc>
                  <handDesc>
                     <handNote scope="major" script="nasta_liq" medium="ink"> Probably written in
                        clear <material>black</material> nasta‘līq with <material>red</material>
                        subheaders and markings by by <persName cert="high" key="person_f3560"
                           role="scr" xml:lang="ur-Latn-x-lc">Rā'i Rājā Lāl Jī,
                        1838–1885</persName></handNote>
                  </handDesc>
                  <decoDesc>
                     <decoNote type="headpiece"><label>Headpiece:</label> Folio <locus from="1b"
                           to="1b">1b</locus> bears a scalloped domed headpiece with gilt palmette
                        foliate scrollwork on an ultramarine ground and an uninscribed central
                        cartouche, and four vertical radiating lines.</decoNote>

                     <decoNote type="lineFill"><label>Line Fill:</label>All lines outlined with
                        cloud bands of single painted gold ink outlined in thin black.</decoNote>
                     <decoNote type="marginal"><label>Ruling:</label> Text margins ruled in single
                        lines of <material>red lead</material> surrounded by single
                           <material>gold</material> internal and external lines, the latter
                        outlined withe thin single interior and double exterior black lines,
                        surrounded by thin single red and blue lines.
                     </decoNote>
                  </decoDesc>
                  <additions>
                     <lb/>
                     <label>Inscriptions:</label> The <locus from="ia" to="ia">right flyleaf a side
                        (f. ia)</locus> bears the title and name of former owner <persName
                        type="supplied" key="person_f830" role="fmo" change="#role-assignment"
                        >Colonel George William Hamilton</persName> underneath, likely in the hand
                     of his assistant <persName role="wst ins" key="person_f6587">Muhīn
                        Dās</persName>.<lb/>
                     <label>Bookplates:</label> The <locus from="Inner_back_cover"
                        to="Inner_back_cover">left pastedown</locus>: <q xml:lang="en">Bibliotheca
                        Lindesiana</q> with pencilled shelfmark <q xml:lang="en">F/11</q>, and <q
                        xml:lang="en"><hi rend="strikethrough">Hamilton</hi> MSS No. <hi
                           rend="strikethrough">567</hi></q>, with the name and number crossed out
                     and <q xml:lang="en">Persian</q> and <q xml:lang="en">650</q> written aside. </additions>
                  <bindingDesc>
                     <binding notBefore="1775" notAfter="1838">
                        <p>Probably bound in <placeName cert="high"
                              ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7001535" key="place_7001535"
                              >Delhi</placeName> for <persName type="supplied" key="person_f830"
                              role="fmo" change="#role-assignment">Colonel George William
                              Hamilton</persName>.</p>
                        <p>Two bifolia of comparatively heavy-weight, highly flocked paper likely
                           handmade in the <placeName cert="high"
                              ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7000208" key="place_7000208"
                              >Indian subcontinent</placeName> added to the manuscript as endpapers.
                           Sewn all along at two stations through a paper spine lining. Edges
                           roughly trimmed, endbands omitted. Case-bound in a European-style half
                           binding with red goatskin <material>leather</material> for the spine and
                           corners, and boards faced with 'shell' patterned marbled paper featuring
                           predominantly red with green veins, applied to a yellow sheet
                           substrate.</p>
                        <p><dimensions type="binding" unit="mm">
                              <height>271</height>
                              <width>168</width>
                              <depth>7</depth>
                           </dimensions></p>
                        <condition>Handle binding with caution. In fair but stable condition, with
                           extensive abrasion of the marbled paper, especially along the
                           edges.</condition>
                     </binding>
                  </bindingDesc>
                  <sealDesc>
                     <seal type="embossed" subtype="rectangle">
                        <p><label>1:</label> Folios <locus from="1a" to="1b">1</locus> and <locus
                              from="6a" to="6b">6</locus> bear an illegible rectangular relief-cut
                           blind embossed stamp, surrounded by foliate scrollwork and surmounted by
                           a crown:<lb/>
                           <dimensions type="stamp" unit="mm">
                              <height>13</height>
                              <width>12</width>
                           </dimensions></p>
                     </seal>
                  </sealDesc>
               </physDesc>
               <history>
                  <origin>While unsigned and uncredited, it appears likely completed by <persName cert="high" key="person_f3560"
                     role="scr" xml:lang="ur-Latn-x-lc">Rā'i Rājā Lāl Jī,
                     1838–1885</persName> for
                        <persName type="supplied" key="person_f830" role="fmo pat"
                        change="#role-assignment">Colonel George William Hamilton
                        (1807-1868)</persName>, who served in <placeName
                        ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7000208" key="place_7000208"
                        >India</placeName>
                     <date calendar="#Gregorian" from="1823" to="1867"> from 1823 to 1867</date>,
                     latterly as Commissioner in <origPlace cert="high"
                        ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7001535" key="place_7001535"
                        >Delhi</origPlace> undated, but probably between <origDate
                        calendar="#Gregorian" cert="high" notBefore="1861" notAfter="1868"
                        >1862–1867</origDate> during Hamilton's tenure there.</origin>
                  <provenance>
                     <p>Hamilton ultimately acquired over a thousand Indian and Persian manuscripts,
                        from which the <orgName ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/134857252">British
                           Museum</orgName> purchased 352 from his widow, <persName
                           key="person_f8470" role="fmo">Charlotte Logie Hamilton
                           (1817–1893)</persName>, now held in the <orgName
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/121814978">British Library</orgName>.</p>
                  </provenance>
                  <provenance><p>
                        <persName role="fmo" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/97751058/"
                           key="person_97751058"> Alexander Lindsay, 25th Earl of Crawford
                           (1812–1880)</persName> purchased the remainder of Hamilton's collection
                     in <date calendar="#Gregorian" when="1868">1868</date>, then moved it to <orgName
                        ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/295427552" key="person_295427552">Bibliotheca
                        Lindesiana</orgName> at Haigh Hall, <placeName
                           ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7010384" key="place_7010384"
                           >Wigan</placeName>.  </p>
                  </provenance>
                  <provenance><p>Purchased by <persName role="dnr" key="person_f6379"
                           change="#prov-markup">Enriqueta Rylands (1843–1908)</persName> in <date
                           calendar="#Gregorian" when="1901">1901</date> from <persName role="fmo"
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/9985420/" key="person_9985420">James Ludovic
                           Lindsay, 26th Earl of Crawford (1847–1913)</persName>.</p></provenance>
                  <acquisition>
                     <p>Bequeathed by <persName key="person_f6379" change="#prov-markup">Enriqueta
                           Rylands (1843–1908)</persName> in <date calendar="#Gregorian" when="1908"
                           >1908</date> to the <orgName type="corporation" role="rps"
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/312795145/">John Rylands Library</orgName>,
                           <placeName ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7010477"
                           key="place_7010477">Manchester</placeName>.</p>
                  </acquisition>
               </history>
